title: Production of neon-24 and sodium-24 in the 1-3 GeV proton bombardment of copper, silver, gold, and uranium targets

x4freetext: Cosmotron
after dissolution of the target foils in 1.8 to 2.5 min
after the end of irradiation Ne-24 was separated from
Na-24 within 20 sec. After Ne-24 had decayed to Na-24
this nuclide was used in the different fractions either
for the determination of the cumulative production of
Ne-24 or the independent production of Na-24.
Targets consisted of three 0.001 inch Al-foils and
three 0.001 to 0.003 inch foils of the specified
metal. The middle foils were used for monitoring and
to determine Na-24 and Ne-24, respectively.

x4codes.shortRef: Jour: Annual Review of Nuclear and Part.Sci., Vol.13, p.261 (1963)

x4freetext: used when sufficient Na-24 activity was present
used at lower Na-24 activities. a few samples with
very low counting rates were measured on low-level
beta counters.
In approximately half the experiments the cumulative
yield of Na-24 was measured also in one of the
remaining foils. These cross sections agreed to +-15%
with those of the sums of cumulative Ne-24 plus
independent Na-24.
Additional external irradiations of Cu and Ag targets
at 3 GeV using a continuous flow system to collect the
Ne-24 produced during the irradiation yielded values
which agreed within +-10% with those obtained from
internal irradiations. Thus No appreciable amount of
Ne-24 compared to Na-24 was lost during the internal
irradiations as a result of target heating.
In general two independent experiments were performed
for determination of the cross section ratios. Four
experiments were made for Ag and U with 1 GeV protons
and three experiments for Au with 3 GeV protons.

x4freetext: The ratio-errors given are the mean
deviations of several runs or 10% if the mean deviation
is smaller than this figure as stated by the author.
Uncertainties of +-(10 to 15) seconds in the separation
times, the quantity known with least precision,
resulted in uncertainties of 5 to 10%. No further
details are given.
